{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625479"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:25:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:25:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17028"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17028"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0.44,0.06,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68311"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9718"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17028"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53768"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4938"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22865"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22870"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68311"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECodeine is commonly prescribed for mild to moderate pain relief.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism by which codeine produces its analgesic effect?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct activation of descending pain pathways","Blockade of substance P release","Direct binding to mu opioid receptors","Inhibition of prostaglandin synthesis","Hepatic conversion to morphine by CYP2D6"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe analgesic effect of codeine relies on its \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatic conversion to morphine by CYP2D6\u003C/strong\u003E. Approximately 10% of the administered codeine dose undergoes this conversion. The resulting morphine then binds to mu opioid receptors to produce analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect activation of descending pain pathways\u003C/strong\u003E: codeine cannot directly activate pain pathways as it requires conversion to morphine first to exert any significant analgesic effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlockade of substance P release\u003C/strong\u003E: while morphine can affect substance P release, this is a downstream effect rather than codeine\u0027s primary mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect binding to mu opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: codeine has a very weak affinity for opioid receptors and must be converted to morphine to produce meaningful receptor activation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of prostaglandin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the mechanism of action of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs, not codeine or other opioid medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIndividual response to codeine varies due to genetic polymorphisms in CYP2D6. Poor metabolisers may experience minimal analgesia, while ultra-rapid metabolisers may be at risk of toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Codeine is a prodrug that requires conversion to morphine by cytochrome P450 2D6 for analgesic effect.","Approximately 10% of codeine is converted to morphine in the liver.","Genetic variations in CYP2D6 affect individual response to codeine therapy."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53768"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17028"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53768"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T16:00:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T16:01:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9718"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68311"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"